hook.real_world_problem:
Zerodha scales to 5 Spring Boot instances at market peak. A @Scheduled job runs end-of-day settlement at 3:30pm:

```java
@Scheduled(cron = "0 30 15 * * MON-FRI")
public void runSettlement() {
    // This runs on ALL 5 instances simultaneously!
    settlementService.calculatePositions();  // 5× calculations
    ledgerService.postEntries();             // 5× ledger entries → duplicate debits!
    notificationService.sendStatements();   // 5× emails to each user!
}
```

Result: every user gets 5 settlement emails. Every position calculated 5 times. Some ledger entries duplicated → wrong balances.

**The fix — Redis distributed lock:**
```java
@Scheduled(cron = "0 30 15 * * MON-FRI")
public void runSettlement() {
    String lockKey = "lock:settlement:" + LocalDate.now();
    String lockVal = UUID.randomUUID().toString();  // unique owner ID

    // Atomic SETNX + EX: acquire lock OR fail instantly:
    Boolean acquired = redis.opsForValue()
        .setIfAbsent(lockKey, lockVal, Duration.ofMinutes(10));

    if (!Boolean.TRUE.equals(acquired)) {
        log.info("Settlement already running on another instance — skipping");
        return;  // another instance has the lock
    }

    try {
        settlementService.calculatePositions();  // runs ONCE across all 5 instances
        ledgerService.postEntries();
        notificationService.sendStatements();
    } finally {
        // Safe release: only delete if WE own the lock (value check):
        String currentVal = redis.opsForValue().get(lockKey);
        if (lockVal.equals(currentVal)) {
            redis.delete(lockKey);
        }
    }
}
```

Now regardless of cluster size: exactly one instance runs settlement. The others detect the lock and skip. The lock expires automatically if the instance crashes.

concept_explanation.setnx_lock:
**SETNX distributed lock — the core pattern:**

```java
import org.springframework.data.redis.core.RedisTemplate;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import java.time.Duration;
import java.util.UUID;

@Service
public class RedisDistributedLock {
    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;

    RedisDistributedLock(RedisTemplate<String,String> r) { redis = r; }

    /**
     * Acquire a lock. Returns the lock value (owner ID) if acquired, null if not.
     * Caller must store the returned value to release the lock later.
     */
    public String tryAcquire(String lockKey, Duration ttl) {
        String lockValue = UUID.randomUUID().toString();  // unique per acquisition

        // SET lockKey lockValue NX EX ttlSeconds
        // NX = only set if Not eXists (atomic SETNX)
        // EX = set expiry simultaneously (atomic — no separate EXPIRE call needed)
        Boolean acquired = redis.opsForValue()
            .setIfAbsent(lockKey, lockValue, ttl);

        return Boolean.TRUE.equals(acquired) ? lockValue : null;
    }

    /**
     * Release the lock ONLY if we own it.
     * Uses value comparison to avoid releasing someone else's lock.
     */
    public boolean release(String lockKey, String lockValue) {
        // Check-then-delete is NOT atomic without Lua.
        // Simple version (race condition exists but is acceptable for most use cases):
        String current = redis.opsForValue().get(lockKey);
        if (lockValue.equals(current)) {
            redis.delete(lockKey);
            return true;
        }
        return false;  // lock already expired or taken by another
    }

    /**
     * Safe pattern for one-time execution.
     */
    public boolean executeOnce(String lockKey, Duration ttl, Runnable task) {
        String lockValue = tryAcquire(lockKey, ttl);
        if (lockValue == null) return false;  // already locked

        try {
            task.run();
            return true;
        } finally {
            release(lockKey, lockValue);
        }
    }
}
```

**Why unique lock value (not just '1')?**
```
Scenario without unique value:
  Instance A: acquires lock 'lock:settlement' with value '1'
  Instance A: settlement takes longer than TTL (10 min)
  TTL expires! Lock auto-released by Redis.
  Instance B: sees lock available → acquires it with value '1'
  Instance B: starts running settlement (second run!)
  Instance A: finishes, calls redis.delete('lock:settlement')
              DELETES INSTANCE B's LOCK! Now Instance C can run too.

With unique value (UUID):
  Instance A: acquires with value 'a1b2c3' (UUID)
  TTL expires → Instance B acquires with value 'x7y8z9'
  Instance A: tries to release — gets('lock') = 'x7y8z9' ≠ 'a1b2c3' → won't delete!
  Instance B's lock is safe.
```

concept_explanation.scheduled_task_dedup:
**Deduplicating @Scheduled tasks across cluster:**

```java
@Service
public class ClusterSafeScheduledService {
    private final RedisDistributedLock lock;
    private final String instanceId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

    ClusterSafeScheduledService(RedisDistributedLock l) { lock = l; }

    @Scheduled(cron = "0 30 15 * * MON-FRI")  // 3:30 PM weekdays
    public void endOfDaySettlement() {
        String key = "lock:settlement:" + java.time.LocalDate.now();
        // Date in key: ensures a new lock for each day's settlement
        // If settlement for today already ran, the lock was deleted after completion.
        // If it's still running, the lock exists → other instances skip.

        boolean ran = lock.executeOnce(key, Duration.ofMinutes(15), () -> {
            log.info("[{}] Running settlement — holding distributed lock", instanceId);
            settlementService.process();
            log.info("[{}] Settlement complete — releasing lock", instanceId);
        });

        if (!ran) {
            log.info("[{}] Settlement already running on another instance — skipped", instanceId);
        }
    }

    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 60_000)  // every minute
    public void refreshExpiringCaches() {
        // For recurring jobs: use a short TTL lock to ensure at-most-one concurrent run
        // Different from settlement: multiple runs are expected (just not concurrent)
        String key = "lock:cache-refresh:" + (System.currentTimeMillis() / 60_000);
        lock.executeOnce(key, Duration.ofSeconds(55), () -> {
            cacheRefreshService.refreshHotKeys();
        });
        // Key includes minute window → naturally one run per minute
    }

    private SettlementService settlementService = () -> {};
    private CacheRefreshService cacheRefreshService = () -> {};

    interface SettlementService { void process(); }
    interface CacheRefreshService { void refreshHotKeys(); }
}
```

concept_explanation.idempotency_keys:
**Idempotency keys — prevent duplicate payment processing:**

```java
@Service
public class PaymentIdempotencyService {
    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    private final PaymentRepository paymentRepo;

    PaymentIdempotencyService(
            RedisTemplate<String,String> r, PaymentRepository pr) {
        redis=r; paymentRepo=pr;
    }

    /**
     * Process payment exactly once per idempotency key.
     * Razorpay: each payment request carries an X-Idempotency-Key header.
     * If the same key arrives twice (network retry), return the FIRST result.
     */
    public PaymentResponse processPayment(String idempotencyKey, PaymentRequest req) {
        String lockKey   = "idem:lock:"   + idempotencyKey;
        String resultKey = "idem:result:" + idempotencyKey;

        // Check if already processed (result cached):
        String cached = redis.opsForValue().get(resultKey);
        if (cached != null) {
            log.info("Idempotency hit: returning cached result for key {}", idempotencyKey);
            return deserialize(cached, PaymentResponse.class);
        }

        // Try to acquire processing lock:
        Boolean acquired = redis.opsForValue()
            .setIfAbsent(lockKey, "processing", Duration.ofSeconds(30));

        if (!Boolean.TRUE.equals(acquired)) {
            // Another request is currently processing this key:
            throw new PaymentInProgressException(
                "Payment " + idempotencyKey + " is already being processed");
        }

        try {
            // Double-check: was it processed while we acquired the lock?
            String doubleCheck = redis.opsForValue().get(resultKey);
            if (doubleCheck != null) return deserialize(doubleCheck, PaymentResponse.class);

            // Process the payment:
            PaymentResponse response = paymentRepo.create(req);

            // Cache result for 24 hours (cover retry window):
            redis.opsForValue().set(
                resultKey, serialize(response), Duration.ofHours(24));

            return response;
        } finally {
            redis.delete(lockKey);  // release processing lock
        }
    }

    private String serialize(Object o) { return o.toString(); }  // use Jackson in real code
    private <T> T deserialize(String s, Class<T> c) { return null; }  // stub

    interface PaymentRepository { PaymentResponse create(PaymentRequest r); }
    record PaymentRequest(String merchantId, double amount) {}
    record PaymentResponse(String paymentId, String status) {}
    static class PaymentInProgressException extends RuntimeException {
        PaymentInProgressException(String m) { super(m); }
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.lock_ttl_choice:
**Choosing the right lock TTL:**

```java
// TTL must be > expected task duration:
// Settlement (takes ~5 min): lock TTL = 15 min (3× buffer)
// Cache refresh (takes ~2 sec): lock TTL = 30 sec
// Payment dedup (takes ~200ms): lock TTL = 10 sec
// Batch job (takes ~1 hour): lock TTL = 2 hours

// What happens if TTL is too short?
//   TTL = 5 min, settlement takes 8 min:
//   At 5 min: lock auto-expires → another instance acquires → DUPLICATE RUN!
//   Always: TTL >> expected_duration (3× is a common rule of thumb)

// What happens if TTL is too long?
//   TTL = 1 hour, instance crashes after 10 min:
//   Lock remains for 1 hour → no other instance can run settlement for 1 hour
//   Always: TTL << recovery_window (next expected run time minus now)

// Lock TTL tradeoff:
//   Too short: duplicate runs on crash-recovery overlap
//   Too long: delayed retry after crash
//   Sweet spot: 3× expected duration, within safety margin of next scheduled run

// Lock key includes date/run-period to allow re-run next day/period:
String key = "lock:settlement:" + LocalDate.now();    // re-runnable tomorrow
String key = "lock:report:" + YearMonth.now();         // re-runnable next month
String key = "lock:migration:V5";                      // never re-run same version
```

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
@Service
public class RedisDistributedLock {
    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    RedisDistributedLock(RedisTemplate<String,String> r) { redis=r; }

    public String tryAcquire(String key, Duration ttl) {
        String val = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
        Boolean ok  = redis.opsForValue().setIfAbsent(key, val, ttl);
        return Boolean.TRUE.equals(ok) ? val : null;
    }

    public void release(String key, String expectedValue) {
        String current = redis.opsForValue().get(key);
        if (expectedValue.equals(current)) {
            redis.delete(key);
        }
        // If current != expected: lock expired and re-acquired by another → safe to ignore
    }

    public boolean runOnce(String key, Duration ttl, Runnable task) {
        String val = tryAcquire(key, ttl);
        if (val == null) return false;
        try {
            task.run();
            return true;
        } finally {
            release(key, val);
        }
    }
}
```

